diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with symptoms such as fever, oral ulcers, rash, neurological manifestations like seizures, and autoimmune hemolysis.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.rationale: Although primarily known for affecting the joints, RA can have systemic manifestations including fever and rashes. Hemolytic anemia and oral ulcers are less common but can occur.

diagnoses.name: Evans Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: A rare autoimmune disorder characterized by the combination of autoimmune hemolytic anemia and immune thrombocytopenia. It can associate with other autoimmune symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily associated with skin and connective tissue, can present with systemic symptoms like fever and rare hemolytic anemia. Oral ulcers and rash are also observed.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Features of several autoimmune diseases, including SLE, can present together. Symptoms include fever, rash, and possibly hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Still's Disease (Adult-Onset)
diagnoses.rationale: Characterized by high fevers, rash, and joint pain. Hemolytic anemia and other systemic symptoms can occur.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily known for oral and genital ulcers, uveitis, skin lesions. Systemic involvement can include vascular and neurological systems.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Associated with clotting but can have varied presentation including rash, neurological symptoms, and hematologic abnormalities such as hemolytic anemia.

diagnoses.name: Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: Encompasses a group of disorders that involve inflammation of the blood vessels. Symptoms can include rash, fever, and depending on the type, other symptoms such as seizures.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.rationale: Typically caused by the Epstein-Barr virus. Presents with fever, pharyngitis, and often a maculopapular rash, especially after administration of certain antibiotics. Hemolytic anemia can occur.

diagnoses.description: Behçet's disease
diagnoses.details: A rare disorder causing inflammation in blood vessels, which can lead to symptoms like irritated eyes and vascular anomalies. Neurological symptoms, though rare, can mimic pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.description: Psychogenic Non-epileptic Seizures (PNES)
diagnoses.details: Characterized by pseudoseizures, which are episodes that resemble epileptic seizures but without the characteristic electrical activity in the brain. It can be associated with psychological conditions such as obsessive-compulsive disorder.

diagnoses.description: Lupus
diagnoses.details: A systemic autoimmune condition that may present with vascular anomalies, leukoplakia, and neurological manifestations that could mimic pseudoseizures. It may also have ocular involvement causing irritation.

diagnoses.description: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune condition primarily affecting the glands that produce tears and saliva, leading to dry eyes and mouth. Vascular anomalies and neurological complications like pseudoseizures can occur in more severe cases.

diagnoses.description: Vogt-Koyanagi-Harada Disease
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune disease that targets pigmented tissues, which include those of the eye, leading to severe eye irritation. It often presents with neurological symptoms, which can mimic pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.description: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune disease of the central nervous system that can cause a wide range of symptoms including visual disturbances and neurological manifestations that might be confused with pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.description: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.details: A chronic condition presenting with leukoplakia-like lesions in the mouth. While not directly causing pseudoseizures, the stress of chronic illness might exacerbate psychological issues, leading to psychogenic non-epileptic seizures.

diagnoses.description: Systemic Sclerosis (Scleroderma)
diagnoses.details: A condition characterized by the hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. It can lead to vascular anomalies and in severe cases, may involve the esophagus, leading to leukoplakia.

diagnoses.description: Neurofibromatosis
diagnoses.details: A genetic disorder that causes tumors to form on nerve tissue, potentially causing a wide range of symptoms including vascular anomalies. Neurological manifestations might resemble pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.description: Wegener's Granulomatosis (Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis)
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune disease affecting the blood vessels (vasculitis), which could lead to various symptoms including vascular anomalies. It can also affect the nervous system, potentially causing pseudoseizures.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often features dry eyes along with dry mouth and can associate with systemic symptoms, including fatigue, joint pain, and may contribute to attention deficit due to systemic effects. It does not commonly present with vascular anomalies, hyperferritinemia, or postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome, but autoimmune diseases can have wide-ranging effects and may coexist with other conditions.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos syndrome
diagnoses.description: A group of disorders that affect connective tissues and can present with vascular anomalies, particularly in the vascular subtype. It may include symptoms such as joint hypermobility and skin elasticity. Patients can experience autonomic dysregulation, including postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome, though dry eyes and hyperferritinemia are not typical.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hemolytic Anemia
diagnoses.description: Is a group of disorders characterized by an immune response against the body's own red blood cells, leading to their destruction (hemolysis), which could explain hyperferritinemia. It is associated with various autoimmune and chronic diseases and may indirectly contribute to attention deficit through systemic effects. Vascular anomalies and dry eyes are not directly associated.

diagnoses.name: Iron Overload Disorders
diagnoses.description: Conditions like hereditary hemochromatosis, which lead to excess iron accumulation in the body, represented by hyperferritinemia. Iron overload can damage various organs and lead to a wide range of symptoms, including fatigue and joint pain. It is not directly associated with vascular anomalies, dry eyes, or postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome but can affect overall health significantly.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder characterized by the presence of antiphospholipid antibodies that can lead to vascular anomalies, including thrombosis. While more commonly associated with vascular complications, it could indirectly affect the other symptoms through systemic illness.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition that causes pain all over the body and can accompany various symptoms including fatigue, which may lead to attention deficit. While it does not directly cause vascular anomalies, dry eyes, or postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome, it is often associated with a wide range of systemic symptoms that could overlap with other conditions.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can affect many parts of the body, including the eyes, skin, heart, lungs, and brain. It can present with a range of symptoms, including those aligned with vascular anomalies and may have associations with postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome through dysautonomia. Hyperferritinemia could arise in the context of chronic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Lyme Disease
diagnoses.description: An infectious disease caused by the Borrelia bacteria, spread by ticks. Its symptoms can be varied and widespread, including neurological symptoms that may mimic attention deficit, heart rhythm irregularities that might be related to postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome, and potentially vascular anomalies through inflammatory processes.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis (MS)
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the brain and spinal cord. MS can cause a wide variety of symptoms, including vision problems (though typically not dry eyes in the classic sense), autonomic dysfunction that may include postural orthostatic tachycardia syndrome, and cognitive impairments that could affect attention.

diagnoses.name: Hemophagocytic Lymphohistiocytosis (HLH)
diagnoses.description: A life-threatening condition often caused by an overactive immune system, leading to a wide range of symptoms including hyperferritinemia. While more rare, it can involve a complex array of symptoms beyond those listed here and include multi-system involvement.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition in which blood lacks adequate healthy red blood cells due to insufficient iron, potentially causing fatigue and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin B12 Deficiency
diagnoses.description: A lack of vitamin B12 can lead to anemia and other health issues. It's essential for nerve tissue health, brain function, and the production of red blood cells.

diagnoses.name: Aplastic Anemia
diagnoses.description: A rare, life-threatening anemia caused by a decrease in the bone marrow's ability to produce blood cells.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myelogenous Leukemia (CML)
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer that starts in the bone marrow and affects the blood and bone marrow.

diagnoses.name: Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) Infection
diagnoses.description: A virus that attacks the body's immune system, specifically the CD4 cells (T cells), which may result in a wide range of symptoms and can lead to AIDS.

diagnoses.name: Oral Lichen Planus
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory condition that affects mucous membranes inside the mouth, potentially causing discomfort, redness, and lesions.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, potentially causing anemia and malabsorption issues.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that affects white blood cells, causing a wide range of symptoms including anemia and leukopenia.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that can lead to severe diarrhea, fatigue, weight loss, malnutrition, and complications including anemia.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout the body, leading to numerous symptoms, including mouth sores and other issues related to oral health.

diagnoses.name: Allergic reactions
diagnoses.description: An exaggerated response of the immune system to a substance considered foreign or dangerous.

diagnoses.name: Inflammatory Bowel Disease (IBD)
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by chronic inflammation of the gastrointestinal tract, possibly causing hemorrhoids and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer of the blood and bone marrow that affects white blood cells and can cause leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Fatigue Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A complex disorder characterized by extreme fatigue that can't be explained by any underlying medical condition, potentially linked with chemical sensitivities and difficulty concentrating.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Chemical Sensitivity
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by severe allergic reactions or sensitivities to multiple chemicals.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune disorders
diagnoses.description: Diseases caused by an overactive immune response against the body's own tissues, potentially explaining hypersensitivity reactions and leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Anemia
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by a deficiency of red blood cells or of hemoglobin in the blood, potentially related to chronic diseases that can cause leukocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.description: A condition in which the thyroid gland doesn't produce enough thyroid hormone, potentially leading to difficulty concentrating and hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Fibromyalgia
diagnoses.description: A disorder characterized by widespread musculoskeletal pain accompanied by fatigue, sleep, memory, and mood issues, sometimes related to hypersensitivity reactions.

diagnoses.name: Infections (Bacterial, Viral, Fungal)
diagnoses.description: Infections can cause leukocytosis and hypersensitivity reactions, among other symptoms.

symptoms: dyspnea with normal pulmonary function tests

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.reason: This autoimmune disease can affect multiple systems including kidneys (lupus nephritis), and can cause generalized symptoms such as lymphadenopathy and decreased appetite.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.reason: This condition involves inflammation of blood vessels (vasculitis) which can affect the kidneys, cause lymphadenopathy, and respiratory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.reason: An autoimmune disease that primarily causes dry eyes and dry mouth, but can also lead to kidney disease, lymphadenopathy, and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.reason: Involves the growth of tiny collections of inflammatory cells in different parts of the body, including the lymph nodes; can also affect the kidneys and cause systemic symptoms like decreased appetite.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.reason: Can cause a wide range of symptoms including lymphadenopathy, chronic kidney disease through HIV-associated nephropathy (HIVAN), and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Lymphoma
diagnoses.reason: Cancer of the lymphatic system that can cause lymphadenopathy, affect kidney function indirectly, and cause systemic symptoms such as decreased appetite.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.reason: A chronic inflammatory disorder affecting many joints, including potential systemic effects causing decreased appetite, and can have renal manifestations and cause lymphadenopathy.

diagnoses.name: Tuberculosis
diagnoses.reason: A bacterial infection that can lead to lymphadenitis, affect the kidneys, and cause systemic symptoms like decreased appetite.

diagnoses.name: Post-Streptococcal Glomerulonephritis
diagnoses.reason: Occurs after a streptococcal infection; symptoms can include decreased kidney function and it may be associated with vasculitis and systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Mononucleosis (Epstein-Barr Virus)
diagnoses.reason: Causes swollen lymph nodes, potential for chronic fatigue, decreased appetite, and can affect the liver and kidneys.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylaxis
diagnoses.description: A severe, potentially life-threatening allergic reaction that can occur rapidly, presenting with symptoms such as hypotension, dyspnea, and skin reactions like pruritis and angioedema.

diagnoses.name: Hereditary Angioedema
diagnoses.description: A rare genetic condition causing repeated episodes of swelling (angioedema), possibly with hypotension and abdominal pain, but less commonly causing pruritis.

diagnoses.name: Addison's Disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the adrenal glands causing low production of hormones, leading to symptoms like hypotension, fatigue, and, in some cases, skin changes.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Mastocytosis
diagnoses.description: A disease where mast cells accumulate in the body tissues, causing symptoms like skin lesions, pruritis, dyspnea, and syncope due to vasodilation and hypotension.

diagnoses.name: Anaphylactoid Reaction
diagnoses.description: Similar to anaphylaxis but not caused by an allergic reaction. Symptoms can include dyspnea, hypotension, and skin reaction without the presence of allergen.

diagnoses.name: Septic Shock
diagnoses.description: A severe infection leading to organ dysfunction and dangerously low blood pressure (hypotension), along with possible skin rash or other symptoms due to the body's response.

diagnoses.name: Vasovagal Syncope
diagnoses.description: A common cause of fainting (syncope), often related to stress or pain, leading to a drop in blood pressure (hypotension) and, sometimes, accompanied by shortness of breath (dyspnea).

diagnoses.name: Medication Side Effect
diagnoses.description: Various medications can induce symptoms of hypotension, dyspnea, syncope, pruritis, and angioedema, either as allergic reactions or direct side effects.

diagnoses.name: Cardiogenic Shock
diagnoses.description: A serious condition where the heart suddenly can't pump enough blood to meet the body's needs, leading to hypotension, dyspnea, and potentially syncope.

diagnoses.name: Heart Failure
diagnoses.description: A chronic condition where the heart doesn't pump blood as well as it should, potentially leading to hypotension, dyspnea, and episodes of fainting (syncope).

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.rationale: This autoimmune disease commonly presents with nonscarring alopecia, proteinuria (due to lupus nephritis), leukopenia, and can also include neuropsychiatric lupus manifestations such as psychosis. Chilblains (lupus pernio) may also occur in some patients.

diagnoses.name: Lupus Nephritis
diagnoses.rationale: While part of the systemic involvement in SLE, lupus nephritis specifically relates to the kidney involvement, characterized by significant proteinuria. Other systemic symptoms of SLE, such as nonscarring alopecia, leukopenia, and neurologic symptoms including psychosis, support the diagnosis.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.rationale: MCTD features signs and symptoms of various connective tissue diseases, including SLE. Patients might experience nonscarring alopecia, proteinuria as a sign of renal involvement, leukopenia, and neurologic symptoms including psychosis. Chilblain lupus is also a characteristic feature.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis (RA) with Rheumatoid Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: RA can sometimes lead to rheumatoid vasculitis, which can present with skin conditions like chilblains, alopecia, and systemic symptoms due to organ involvement. RA's systemic nature can occasionally cause kidney damage (proteinuria), leukopenia, and in rare cases, neuropsychiatric symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Cryoglobulinemic Vasculitis
diagnoses.rationale: Cryoglobulinemic vasculitis, associated with chronic infections (e.g., Hepatitis C), autoimmune diseases, or cancers, can manifest with skin lesions (such as chilblains), kidney damage (proteinuria), hematological abnormalities (leukopenia), and in rare cases, mental health issues.

diagnoses.name: Antiphospholipid Syndrome (APS)
diagnoses.rationale: Primarily known for its thrombotic events, APS can sometimes present with skin manifestations, kidney involvement (proteinuria), neurological symptoms (including psychosis), and blood disorders (leukopenia). However, nonscarring alopecia and chilblains are less commonly observed.

diagnoses.name: Sjogren's Syndrome
diagnoses.rationale: Sjogren's syndrome primarily affects the exocrine glands but can also lead to extraglandular manifestations including renal involvement (proteinuria) and hematological abnormalities (leukopenia). Neurological manifestations can occur, albeit psychosis is rare. Alopecia and chilblains could be observed but are not classic presentations.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.rationale: Characterized by inflammation of the muscles and skin, dermatomyositis can manifest with skin changes (including rashes that might resemble chilblains), alopecia, and in some cases proteinuria due to renal involvement, leukopenia, and neuropsychiatric symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Polyarteritis Nodosa (PAN)
diagnoses.rationale: PAN is a systemic necrotizing vasculitis that can involve multiple organs including the skin (chilblains-like lesions), kidneys (proteinuria), and nervous system (including psychosis). Leukopenia and nonscarring alopecia could be observed but are less typical.

diagnoses.name: Behcet's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: A rare inflammatory disorder, Behcet's disease, can present with vascular inflammation leading to symptoms such as skin lesions resembling chilblains, possible kidney involvement (proteinuria), and neurological manifestations. While leukopenia and alopecia are not hallmark features, they can occur in the context of systemic inflammation.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune disease causing widespread inflammation and tissue damage, SLE can lead to thrombocytopenia, lymphopenia, and potentially proteinuria due to kidney involvement.

diagnoses.name: Ataxia-telangiectasia
diagnoses.details: A rare genetic disorder affecting the nervous system, immune system, and other body parts. Features include telangiectasias, immunodeficiencies such as lymphopenia, and potential skin changes.

diagnoses.name: Dermatomyositis
diagnoses.details: An inflammatory disease known for its distinctive skin rash and muscle weakness. It can also cause thrombocytopenia, postinflammatory dyspigmentation, and in chronic cases, proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Scleroderma
diagnoses.details: A group of autoimmune diseases causing hardening and tightening of the skin and connective tissues. It can lead to telangiectasias, proteinuria due to kidney involvement, and various blood abnormalities.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.details: An autoimmune disorder with features of lupus, scleroderma, and polymyositis, including blood abnormalities like thrombocytopenia and lymphopenia, telangiectasias, and potentially proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.details: Human Immunodeficiency Virus/AIDS can lead to lymphopenia due to its direct effects on the immune system. Associated conditions may also result in thrombocytopenia, proteinuria, and skin changes including postinflammatory dyspigmentation.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.details: A long-term condition characterized by the gradual loss of kidney function, which can lead to proteinuria. It may also be associated with secondary thrombocytopenia.

diagnoses.name: Granulomatosis with Polyangiitis
diagnoses.details: Formerly known as Wegener's Granulomatosis, it is a rare disorder causing inflammation of the blood vessels, which could indirectly result in thrombocytopenia and proteinuria.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Thrombocytopenic Purpura (ITP)
diagnoses.details: A blood disorder characterized by an abnormally low number of platelets, leading to thrombocytopenia. It is primarily a diagnosis of exclusion after other conditions have been ruled out.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.details: An inflammation of the blood vessels (vasculitis) that can cause rash, arthritis, abdominal pain, and kidney involvement leading to proteinuria. Thrombocytopenia is less common but may occur.
